<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
In this update:
[1] Thailand
[2] Indonesia
******
[1] Thailand
Date: 9 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties (OIE), Disease Information
[edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current>

Highly pathogenic avian influenza in Thailand: follow-up report No. 10
----------------------------------------------
See also: 2 Apr 2004 (Disease Information 2004; 17[14]: 100, 2 Apr), 26,
19, 12, 5 Mar 2004, 27, 20, 13, 6 Feb 2004, 23 Jan 2004.
Information received on (and up to) 9 Apr 2004 from Dr Yukol Limlamthong,
director general, Department of Livestock Development (DLD), Ministry of
Agriculture and Cooperatives, Bangkok.
New outbreaks:
One outbreak in Chonburi Province, Pangthong District, Nong Tumlung
Subdistrict.
One outbreak in Khonkaen Province, Muang District, None Ton Subdistrict.
Affected population in the new outbreaks: layer hens.
Total number of animals in the new outbreaks:
species/susceptible/cases/deaths/destroyed/slaughtered
avi / ... /... / ... / 11 326 / ...
Diagnosis:
Both outbreaks were detected thanks to intensive clinical surveillance.
Virus isolation, hemagglutination, and hemagglutination inhibition tests at
Regional Veterinary Research and Development Centers (in Chonburi and
Khonkaen), DLD confirmed the diagnosis of highly pathogenic avian influenza
virus type A, sub-type H5.
Epidemiology:
Both outbreaks were detected in provinces where outbreaks have already been
reported.
Control measures during reporting period:
Stamping-out was applied to the 11 326 layers based on matching clinical
criteria.
******
[2] Indonesia
Date: 9 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties(OIE), Disease Information [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current>

Highly pathogenic avian influenza In Indonesia: follow-up report No. 2
----------------------------------------------
See also: 5 Mar 2004 (Disease Information 2004; 17[10]: 73, 5 Mar -- refers
up to 24 Feb), 6 Feb 2004.
Information received on 6 Apr 2004 (refers up to 25 Mar) from Dr Sofjan
Sudarjat, director general of Livestock Services, Department of
Agriculture, Jakarta.
New outbreaks:
1 district in Central Java Province.
2 districts in Bali Province.
New outbreaks affect layers, broilers, Arabian chickens, native chickens,
ducks, small turtle-doves and quails.
Total number of animals in the new outbreaks:
species/susceptible/cases/deaths/destroyed/slaughtered
avi /... / ... / 800 000 / ... / ...
Diagnosis of highly pathogenic avian influenza virus type A, subtype H5N1
made using hemagglutination inhibition test, pathogenicity test at Disease
Investigation Centre Region IV, Yogyakarta and Disease Investigation Centre
Region VI, Denpasar.
Epidemiology:
Source of agent/origin of infection is under investigation.
Mode of spread: movement of live poultry, poultry products and by-products,
egg trays and equipment.
Control measures during reporting period: quarantine, movement control
inside the country, vaccination, zoning.
Control measures during reporting period:
The area is under quarantine and surveillance has been intensified.
